  "+160 kJ because -120 + 80 - 200 rounds to +160 kJ from the total": "",
  "DeltaH_total = -120 + 80 + (-200) = -240 kJ. Using Hess's Law, you add the DeltaH values of each step.": "",
  "A student asks: 'Why do we need Hess's Law if we can just measure DeltaH directly?' The best answer is:": "",
  "Some reactions are too slow, dangerous, or impractical to measure directly in a lab": "",
  "All reactions must use Hess's Law because direct measurement is never accurate": "",
  "Hess's Law gives different results than direct measurement for the same reaction": "",
  "Direct measurement always gives negative values while Hess's Law gives positive": "",
  "Many reactions cannot be measured directly because they are too slow, too dangerous, or produce side reactions. Hess's Law lets us calculate DeltaH from measurable reactions.": "",
  "A textbook lists the DeltaHf of liquid water as -285.8 kJ/mol and gaseous water as -241.8 kJ/mol. The enthalpy of vaporization of water is:": "",
